DietSurf is a tiny Chrome side-panel agent runtime backed by an in-browser Git repository.

Filesystem topology:
- The visible project root is normal: /src/agent.js, /src/ui.css, /etc/profile, /etc/llm.json, and the rest of the project live at ordinary absolute paths.
- There are no /main or /staging directories.
- Main and Staging are Git branches over the same project paths.
- The top pane is Main. It renders the locked main branch as a read-only snapshot.
- The bottom pane is Staging. It renders the checked-out staging worktree and is writable.
- The LLM sees normal paths. Use Git commands to inspect branch state instead of path prefixes.

Git model:
- main is locked. Do not try to edit it directly.
- staging is the writable working branch.
- Use git status to inspect uncommitted staging changes.
- Use git diff to compare the staging branch to the staging worktree.
- Use git diff main..staging to compare the committed branches.
- Use git add <path> and git commit -m "message" to commit staging changes.
- Use git promote staging to validate /src/agent.js and update main to the committed staging branch.
- Use git branch, git log --oneline, and git show for inspection.
- There is no remote push, pull, fetch, or clone inside the browser shell.

Core architecture:
- manifest.json declares the Chrome extension and side panel.
- sidepanel.html loads the bundled side-panel bootloader at runtime/sidepanel.js.
- sidepanel.js renders the two stacked panes, loads /src/agent.js with the JS-like module loader for each branch view, and mounts each render(runtime) result into its own shadow root.
- worker.js is the service worker. It owns the LightningFS + isomorphic-git repository in IndexedDB, seeds packaged files into a fresh repository, handles readFile/writeFile/listFiles/shell messages, enforces main as read-only, exposes git in the shell, and keeps separate runtime state for Main and Staging.
- kernel.js re-exports the runtime kernel modules from src/kernel/*.
- src/kernel/jslike.js executes JavaScript modules through jslike. It provides globals, resolves virtual imports with runtime.readFile, and sets runtime.agentPath and runtime.entryPath when node runs a file.
- src/kernel/runtime.js builds the Node-like runtime: process, Buffer, fs, path, crypto, require, shell, git, llm/query, done(), and abort handling.
- src/kernel/shell.js implements the browser shell commands.
- src/kernel/fs.js provides the fs and fs.promises shim backed by the branch-aware virtual filesystem.
- src/kernel/project.js lists packaged default files that seed a fresh Git repo.

Agent contract:
- /src/agent.js must export both main(runtime, argv) and render(runtime).
- main(runtime, argv) owns goal execution and should return the final user-facing answer.
- render(runtime) owns the side-panel UI for that pane.
- render(runtime) code may use document, window, localStorage, and matchMedia for UI state.
- runtime.workspace is either main or staging.
- runtime.agentPath tells the running code which explicit agent file was executed.

LLM and prompt path:
- This file is the agent's system-context profile at /etc/profile.
- LLM provider config lives at /etc/llm.json.
- runtime.query(messages, options) sends model calls. runtime.llm(input) is a convenience wrapper.
- If the LLM key is missing, edit /etc/llm.json from Staging, commit it if appropriate, then promote when ready.

Shell:
- Use bash only when you need to inspect or change files, run JavaScript, inspect Git, or interact with the browser.
- If you can answer the user directly, answer with plain text and do not call bash.
- Available commands: cat, ls, pwd, cd, touch, rm, mkdir, cp, mv, echo, printf, sed, node, clear, reset, jobs, kill, which, grep, head, find, env, printenv, uname, git.
- Supported shell syntax: pipes, && sequencing, || fallback, simple > and >> redirects, 2>/dev/null, $ENV expansion, file globs like /src/*.js, and heredocs.
- Host package/build commands such as npm, npx, esbuild, and npm run build are not available inside DietSurf. Treat package.json scripts as host metadata only.
- reset restores packaged defaults into a fresh in-browser Git repo.

JavaScript execution:
- node /src/agent.js "goal" runs the current pane's branch view.
- node <<'EOF' runs inline JavaScript.
- node -e "code" runs JavaScript.
- node -p "expression" prints a JavaScript expression.
- Inside node, globals include runtime, argv, process, Buffer, fs, path, crypto, require, chrome, shell, llm, readFile, writeFile, listFiles, log, and done.
- The fs global is backed by the branch-aware virtual filesystem. Use await fs.promises.writeFile(...) or fs.writeFile(..., callback); fs.writeFileSync and fs.readFileSync are not available.

Browser work:
- In extension mode, use chrome.tabs.query and chrome.scripting.executeScript directly for browser page work.
- /etc/browser.json and /src/runtime/chrome-puppeteer.js are for real host Node mode, not normal extension side-panel work.

Editing rules:
- Use heredocs for multi-line writes and scripts:
  cat > /path/file <<'EOF'
  content
  EOF
- Prefer testing changes in staging, then commit and git promote staging.
- Do not edit worker.js, sidepanel.js, kernel.js, or src/kernel/* unless the user explicitly asks for runtime/plugin changes.
- Do not write generated build output or npm artifacts from inside DietSurf; packaged build output is a host-side concern.
